{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4446c526-8da3-4da1-9a28-8c5e6d8356f3","content":"\n\n`SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` tells the MAUI **layout engine** not to add safe-area padding, but it doesn't make the native window draw behind system bars. You need **platform-level** configuration too.\n\n**Android** — in `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n    WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window!, false);\n    Window!.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n    Window!.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n}\n```\n\nThis tells Android to let your content draw behind the status/nav bars.\n\n**iOS** — also add the platform-specific flag:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;\n             assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"\n             SafeAreaEdges=\"None\">\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n**In short:** `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` handles MAUI's layout layer, but each platform also has its own \"fit content inside system bars\" behavior that must be disabled separately. On Android that's `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(false)` + transparent bars; on iOS it's `UseSafeArea=\"False\"`.\n\n> **Note:** On Android 15+ (API 35), edge-to-edge is enforced by default, so `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows` may already be effectively false — in that case check that your theme/styles aren't re-adding `fitsSystemWindows=\"true\"` or that a parent layout isn't adding its own padding.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"94117197-a5db-4b02-8897-0a22be2f2cb8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is working on a .NET MAUI app targeting .NET 10 and wants an image to go edge-to-edge (behind status bar and navigation bar), but setting `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage isn't working.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. Let me think about what's needed:\n\nIn .NET MAUI, to achieve edge-to-edge content that goes behind system bars, you need to:\n\n1. **Set the page to ignore safe area insets** — `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` is correct for this, but it only tells the page not to add padding for safe areas.\n\n2. **Enable edge-to-edge display** — In .NET MAUI on Android, starting with .NET 9+, Android 15 (API 35) enforces edge-to-edge by default. \n\nFor older versions or explicit control, there might be additional configuration needed. On iOS, `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` should work but I need to verify there's no default padding interfering. On Android with .NET 9 and later, edge-to-edge is already enforced, though there could be other factors preventing the image from extending properly. for it to work properly, you might need to handle the `Window.DecorFitsSystemWindows` or similar settings.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. In .NET MAUI:\n\n- `Page.IgnoreSafeArea` was a thing in Xamarin.Forms\n- In .NET MAUI, there's `SafeArea` handling\n\nWait, I should think about this more carefully for .NET 10 (which would be the latest in April 2026).\n\nThe key issues are typically:\n\n1. **`SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"`** - This is correct to tell the layout not to add padding for safe areas.\n\n2. **On Android**, you also need to make sure the app is drawing behind system bars. This typically involves:\n   - Setting `WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(window, false)` or the newer edge-to-edge API\n   - Making status bar and navigation bar transparent\n\n3. **On iOS**, `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` should be sufficient, but you may also need to ensure the image's layout isn't constrained.\n\nFor .NET MAUI on Android 15+, edge-to-edge is enforced by default, but on older versions you need to explicitly opt in. Since you're on .NET 10, the main thing is ensuring `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` is set and that Android is configured to draw behind the system bars. Setting DecorFitsSystemWindows to false...\n\nThe real issue is that `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` handles the MAUI layout side, but the native Android window needs to be configured to actually render behind the system bars, and then those bars should be made transparent so the content shows through properly. I'm realizing I need to be more precise about the MAUI APIs here—`SafeAreaEdges` might not be the right property, and the platform-specific approach differs between iOS and Android. On iOS, it's typically `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"false\"`, while Android's edge-to-edge behavior depends on the target API level and might already be default on Android 15+, so the native window configuration I mentioned could be redundant or need adjustment depending on their setup.","outputTokens":2400},"id":"c17cebb1-d7a7-432b-9273-5cdae2389cba","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:05:09.951Z","parentId":"fa5d915f-0054-416e-9540-1536bc5b272a"}
